ownedComment.body: At least one of these aggregated classes must be present. If using multiple instances, producers must take care to ensure they represent the same location.
When there are multiple instances of this class the attribute linearElementReferenceModel in the associated LinearElement should be populated to explain the instance.
The order of the locations in the itinerary are specified by the 'index' qualifier. There must be at least two locations.
When there are multiple instances of AlertCLinear they should represent the same location using different location tables.
When there are multiple instances of AlertCArea, they should represent the same area using different location tables.
Any LinearLocation must have an instance of at least one of these classes. If using multiple instances, producers must take care to ensure they represent the same location.
When there are multiple instances of this class the attribute linearElementReferenceModel in the associated LinearElement should be populated to explain the instance.
At least one of these aggregated classes must be present. If using multiple instances of the aggregated classes, producers must take care to ensure they represent the same location.
When there are multiple instances of AlertCPoint, they should represent the same point using different location tables.
The absolute, interpolative and relative methods relate directly to the methods defined in ISO 19148 (LR_LRMType).
Either roadName or roadNumber or both must be populated for the LinearElement instance to be valid.

index = 1..n
Provision of intermediate points are optional, but where provided they are ordered by the "index" qualifier to correspond with their order of appearance along the linear element from the start point.

Coordinates defined according to the European Terrestrial Reference System 1989 (ETRS89) which was coincident with ITRS in 1989. This is the European implementation of ITRS, but unlike ITRS and WGS84 it is centred on Europe. ETRS89 is the EU recommended frame of reference for geodata in Europe.

Coordinates defined according to the European Terrestrial Reference System 1989 (ETRS89) which was coincident with WGS84 in 1989. This is the European implementation of ITRS, but unlike ITRS and WGS84 it is centred on Europe. ETRS89 is the EU recommended frame of reference for geodata in Europe.
Each occurance must be mutually exclusive

NamedArea in namespace LocationReferencing is a specialisation of NamedArea in NameSpace Common, to support a generic hook system between the two namespaces.
